\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 4. A. crassifolia} L.,{\i  Mantissa} 37 (1767) ({\i A. tomentosa} Ten.). Shoots woody at the base, usually glaucous-pruinose, often with long, patent hairs. Stems 15-45 cm, often solitary, erect or geniculate-ascending; middle internodes 1-3 times as long as the leaves. Leaves 15-30(-40) × 1*5-2 mm, lanceolate to broadly linear, usually brownish when dry, thickish, more or less obtuse, often conspicuously crowded at the base of the stem, often in pairs from middle of stem upwards; midrib comprising less than 3/4 of width of leaf; margin distinctly revolute. Inflorescence pyramidal; partial inflorescences more or less capitate. Corolla 4·7-6·3 mm, hypocrateriform, yellowish, densely patent-hairy, sometimes subglabrous; tube 2-3 times as long as lobes. Fruit 1·5-2·5 mm, hairy. {\i Calcareous rocks near the coast. • S.Italy} ({\i near Napoli}); {\i Sardegna} ({\i Tavolara}). It Sa.
